**3. Counting in Binary System**

Since we only have two digits (0 and 1), counting in binary is very simple but works exactly like decimal counting.

**The Rule:** When you reach the highest digit (which is 1), you reset it to 0 and carry 1 to the next position on the left.

Let's count from 0 to 15 in binary and see the pattern:

| **Decimal Number** | **Binary Number** | **Why? (Place Values)** |
| :---: | :---: | :--- |
| 0 | 0 | Starting point. |
| 1 | 1 | One. |
| 2 | 10 | We reached '1', so we carry over. (1×2¹ + 0×2⁰ = 2) |
| 3 | 11 | (1×2¹ + 1×2⁰ = 3) |
| 4 | 100 | Reached '11', carry over to next place. (1×4) |
| 5 | 101 | (1×4 + 0×2 + 1×1) |
| 6 | 110 | (1×4 + 1×2 + 0×1) |
| 7 | 111 | (1×4 + 1×2 + 1×1) |
| 8 | 1000 | Reached '111', carry over to 8s place. |
| 9 | 1001 | |
| 10 | 1010 | |
| 11 | 1011 | |
| 12 | 1100 | |
| 13 | 1101 | |
| 14 | 1110 | |
| 15 | 1111 | |

