**5. Converting Decimal Number to Binary Numbers**

To convert a decimal number to binary, we use the **Repeated Division by 2** method.

**Steps:**
1. Divide the decimal number by 2.
2. Write down the **remainder** (it will always be 0 or 1).
3. Divide the quotient again by 2.
4. Keep repeating until the quotient becomes 0.
5. Read the remainders **from bottom to top** (reverse order).

---

**📝 Example: Convert (13)₁₀ to Binary**

| Step | Division | Quotient | Remainder | Bit |
| :---: | :--- | :---: | :---: | :---: |
| 1 | 13 ÷ 2 | 6 | 1 | Least Significant Bit (LSB) |
| 2 | 6 ÷ 2 | 3 | 0 | |
| 3 | 3 ÷ 2 | 1 | 1 | |
| 4 | 1 ÷ 2 | 0 | 1 | Most Significant Bit (MSB) |

Now, read the remainders from **bottom to top**: **1101**.

**Answer:** (13)₁₀ = **(1101)₂**

---

**📊 Decimal to Binary Conversion Flowchart**

```mermaid
graph TD
    Start[Start with Decimal Number: e.g., 13] --> A[Divide by 2]
    A --> B{Is Quotient Zero?}
    B -->|No| C["Write Remainder (0 or 1)"]
    C --> D[Make Quotient the new number]
    D --> A
    B -->|Yes| E[Collect all remainders]
    E --> F[Read remainders from Bottom to Top]
    F --> G[This is the Binary Number]
    
    style Start fill:#9cf,stroke:#333
    style G fill:#f9f,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px
```

